04341nam a22006375i 9780691190136DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20182019nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806911901367 a10.1515/97806911901362doi  a(DE-B1597)502972  a(OCoLC)1083623212  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aMAT0060002bisacsh04a512.788223  aAK 24200qBVB2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/2557:1 aKernighan, Brian W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMillions, Billions, Zillions :bDefending Yourself in a World of Too Many Numbers /cBrian W. Kernighan. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (176 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter 1: Getting Started -- tChapter 2: Millions, Billions, Zillions -- tChapter 3: Big Numbers -- tChapter 4: Mega, Giga, Tera, and Beyond -- tChapter 5: Units -- tChapter 6: Dimensionality -- tChapter 7: Milestones -- tChapter 8: Specious Precision -- tChapter 9: Lies, Damned Lies, and Statistics -- tChapter 10: Graphical Trickery -- tChapter 11: Bias -- tChapter 12: Arithmetic -- tChapter 13: Estimation -- tChapter 14: Self Defense -- tFurther Reading -- tFigure Credits0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn essential guide to recognizing bogus numbers and misleading dataNumbers are often intimidating, confusing, and even deliberately deceptive-especially when they are really big. The media loves to report on millions, billions, and trillions, but frequently makes basic mistakes or presents such numbers in misleading ways. And misunderstanding numbers can have serious consequences, since they can deceive us in many of our most important decisions, including how to vote, what to buy, and whether to make a financial investment. In this short, accessible, enlightening, and entertaining book, leading computer scientist Brian Kernighan teaches anyone-even diehard math-phobes-how to demystify the numbers that assault us every day.With examples drawn from a rich variety of sources, including journalism, advertising, and politics, Kernighan demonstrates how numbers can mislead and misrepresent. In chapters covering big numbers, units, dimensions, and more, he lays bare everything from deceptive graphs to speciously precise numbers. And he shows how anyone-using a few basic ideas and lots of shortcuts-can easily learn to recognize common mistakes, determine whether numbers are credible, and make their own sensible estimates when needed.Giving you the simple tools you need to avoid being fooled by dubious numbers, Millions, Billions, Zillions is an essential survival guide for a world drowning in big-and often bad-data.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aData mining. 0aNumbers, Complex. 7aMATHEMATICS / Counting & Numeration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060659140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691190136zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691190136423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691190136/original  a978-3-11-060659-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_MTPY  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MTPY  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK